last_simulation.raw_response:
{
  "simulation_overview": "You’re at a crossroads with two appealing job offers and want to negotiate for the best possible terms. By applying the Decisional Balance technique, you systematically lay out the pros and cons of accepting, declining, and counter-offering for each role. This helps clarify which offer aligns best with your priorities (such as compensation, growth, culture, manager fit, and work-life balance) and where negotiation could shift the balance. As you fill in the decisional grids, you identify areas ripe for negotiation—like salary, remote work, or professional development—and use targeted questions to resolve uncertainties. This process enables you to make a confident, well-informed choice and communicate your decision effectively.",
  "scenario_variations": [
    {
      "name": "What if both employers respond positively to your counter-offers?",
      "outcome": "You receive improved offers from both companies, increasing your options but potentially making the decision harder.",
      "guidance": "Update your decisional balance grids with the new terms. Re-rate importance and certainty for each criterion. Pay close attention to how the changes affect your top priorities and whether any new deal-breakers or differentiators emerge. If the offers are now very close, run a 'regret test' (imagine accepting each and see which feels better) and consider long-term growth potential."
    },
    {
      "name": "What if one employer withdraws their offer after your negotiation?",
      "outcome": "You lose one option, which may feel disappointing or risky.",
      "guidance": "Review your decisional balance for the remaining offer to ensure it still meets your must-haves. Reflect on whether the negotiation approach was too aggressive or if the employer’s response reveals something about their culture. Use this as a learning opportunity for future negotiations and, if needed, reach out to your network for additional opportunities."
    }
  ],
  "cautions": [
    "Overcomplicating the grid with too many criteria can lead to analysis paralysis—focus on your top 5 priorities.",
    "Assigning importance or certainty scores based on emotion rather than facts can skew the results; strive for objectivity.",
    "Failing to close information gaps before deciding may result in unexpected surprises post-acceptance.",
    "Negotiating too aggressively or without clear rationale may risk alienating employers or leading to rescinded offers.",
    "Ignoring long-term consequences in favor of short-term gains can result in regret down the line."
  ],
  "recommended_follow_up": [
    "Draft your decisional balance grids for both offers, including negotiation possibilities.",
    "List any unknowns or deal-breakers and contact recruiters/hiring managers to clarify them.",
    "Prepare a clear, respectful counter-offer for your preferred role, highlighting your rationale.",
    "Set a decision deadline to prevent endless deliberation.",
    "After making your choice, thank both employers and communicate your decision professionally."
  ]
}

